    "translations": {
      "en": {
        "summary": "Imam al-Baqir (AS) interprets Quran 2:83 (‘Speak beautifully to the people’) by establishing a golden rule of speech: one should say to others what is better than what one would wish to hear oneself. He then contrasts the traits Allah detests — habitual cursing, insulting believers, obscenity, and importunate begging — with those He loves: modesty, forbearance, virtue, and self-restraint. This teaching was delivered in the context of early Islamic community building, where interpersonal conduct was central to the cohesion of the believers.",
        "key_terms": {
          "حسنا": "husnan — beautifully, kindly; good speech",
          "اللعان": "al-la’an — habitual/persistent curser (intensive form)",
          "السباب": "al-sabbab — habitual insulter (intensive form)",
          "الطعان": "al-ta’an — habitual condemner/slanderer",
          "الحيي": "al-hayiyy — the modest, one with haya (modesty/shame)",
          "الحليم": "al-halim — the forbearing, the gentle/patient",
          "المتعفف": "al-muta’affif — the self-restrained, one who guards one’s chastity and dignity"
        },
        "seo_question": "What does Islam say about speaking kindly to people?"
      },
      "ur": {
